div.div: People frequently spend unnecessary time searching for physical items, even in small homes or workplaces, which reduces efficiency and causes frustration. Most existing inventory tools provide only list-based records and offer little intuitive information about real spatial location of objects.

A visual system that mirrors actual spaces can make item lookup and management far more natural. By allowing users to recreate their floor plans and furniture, such an application enables fast orientation and easy relocation of items without requiring intensive prior training.

div.div: The system provides a visual environment for managing the location of physical items within real spaces. Users can create their own rooms and furniture layouts and use them as an interactive map for managing their inventory.

The application supports creation of custom floor plans, design of furniture structures, and definition of reusable shapes. Items can be placed directly into these virtual spaces, moved between locations, and organized inside furniture in a way that mirrors reality. Items can also represent a hierarchical structure, allowing parent and child items to be modeled naturally. A dedicated item location view then guides the user to the exact position of the selected object.

The editors offer essential editing tools for floors, furniture, and shapes, including dragging, resizing, and rotating elements, as well as zooming and panning the camera for easy navigation. Shapes can be nested to create multi-level or composite structures. Placement is unrestricted, allowing work within an effectively infinite space. Undo and redo features ensure that changes can be made safely without risk.
List pages give users an overview of all items, shapes, furniture, and floors, with options to edit, delete, search and sort elements.

Combined, these features provide a flexible environment for modeling, managing, and locating items in personal or small-business spaces. The tool is designed to support common inventory tasks without requiring advanced technical knowledge.
